{{Infobox instrument | name = Alligator drum | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | background = percussion | names = | classification = Membranophone | hornbostel_sachs = 211.2 | hornbostel_sachs_desc = Tubular drums | inventors = | developed = China | timbre = | volume = | attack = | decay = | range = | pitch = | related = | musicians = | builders = | articles = }}
The '''alligator drum''' is a type of [[drum]] once used in [[Neolithic China]], made from clay and alligator hides.
Alligator drums have been found over a broad area at the [[Neolithic]] sites from modern [[Shandong]] in the east to [[Qinghai]] in the west, dating to a period of 5500–2350 BC. In literary records, drums manifested shamanistic characteristics and were often used in ritual ceremonies.<ref>Liu, Li (2007). ''The Chinese Neolithic: Trajectories to Early States''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-01064-0}}. p. 123</ref> Drums covered with alligator skin for ceremonial use are mentioned in the ''[[Shijing]]''.<ref>Sterckx, Roel (2002). ''The Animal and the Daemon in Early China''. New York: State University of New York Press. {{ISBN|0-7914-5270-0}}. p. 125.</ref><ref>Porter, Deborah Lynn (1996). ''From Deluge to Discourse: Myth, History, and the Generation of Chinese Fiction''. New York: State University of New York Press. {{ISBN|0-7914-3034-0}}. p 53.</ref>
During the Archaic period, [[Chinese alligator|alligator]]s probably lived along the east coast of China, including southern [[Shandong]]. The earliest alligator drums, comprising a wooden frame covered with alligator skin, are found in the archaeological sites at [[Dawenkou]] (4100–2600 BC), as well as several sites of [[Longshan culture|Longshan]] (3000–2000 BC) in Shandong and [[Taosi]] (2300– 1900 BC) in southern [[Shanxi]].<ref>Liu, Li (2007). ''The Chinese Neolithic: Trajectories to Early States''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-01064-0}}.</ref>
